title: Want To Buy:  M1 Garand
postcontent: Looking for a WWll M1 Garand.  Dad and father-in-law were both vets.  Dad served in the Pacific first and then got malaria.  Came back to Fitzsimmons Hospital in Colorado.  Once better he was sent to Europe and was in Patton's Third Army, through the Battle of the Bulge.  Met my mom when she was 15.  He was 19 at the end of the war.  Father-in-law spent 3 1/2 years all in the Pacific making three beach landings.  I remember my dad having a Garand when I was a boy.  Wanting one more for sentimental value, but would still like to shoot it.  If I can find a place locally!  My father-in-law, Gus was the one who shot competitvely into his 80's at the Big Game Hunter club on Frisco Hill.  He was fanatical about his reloading.  Did meat shoots, targets, avid hunter, and carved gunstocks from slabs of wood.  Did all his own checkering.  As a tool and die maker he was all about precision!  He passed in 2007 and we are finally parting with some of his guns. I will be lisitng some here in the future. Thanks!  Ed

Production on these stopped in 1983 and the mag release was moved closer to the trigger guard and the safety moved from the frame to the slide. It is very much not a 92fs, though the 92fs had great improvements this is more of a collectors gun. It comes with the original box and 3 mags. Gun shoots fairly accurate and is reliable as all those Berettas are. This is from wikepedia "Production began in May 1976, and ended in February 1983.
